    "summary": "Vote A: Yes, add Editor — five registers need dedicated prose review",
    "content": "A — Yes. The collection spans five distinct registers (colloquial, analytic, classical Chinese quotation, mathematical/formal, near-lyrical), and maintaining consistency across all eight essays while preserving each register's distinctive quality is a dedicated task. The experts check philosophical accuracy; I (translator) produce the drafts; but neither role is optimized for catching prose-level issues like awkward phrasing, inconsistent tone within a register, paragraph rhythm, or whether the English reads naturally as English rather than as translated Chinese. An Editor would also catch cross-essay consistency problems (e.g., does the way I render the author's exploratory \"thinking-aloud\" register in Essay 1 match how I render it in Essay 3?) that are easy to miss when translating essay by essay. This is especially important because the experiential sequences are load-bearing — if the prose stumbles, the philosophical experiment on the reader fails."
